# SIDE QUEST — "The Last Lantern-Feast"  (requires sq.lantern_feast_threatened)
# Every quest on the long road is about the dead. This one is about the LIVING — and joy as defiance.
# In the Steelshanks ward, old Dot Marigold has run the Lantern-Feast for forty years: one night a year when
# the poor quarter — harvest-marked and faithful alike — dances, courts, eats too much, and floats paper
# lanterns for the year's losses. The Choir has served notice to cancel it: "frivolous in a time of holy
# sorrow." The truth they won't say is worse — a feast where the godless poor are seen dancing, beloved,
# joyful, is a feast where they are people, not cargo, and that is the one thing the harvest cannot allow.
class: LanternFeastSideQuestContent

# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
# "The Last Lantern-Feast" — joy among the doomed as the resistance no machine planned for.
# ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
conversation: sq.feast.thread | The Last Lantern-Feast
node: 0 | Dot Marigold
  *(Dot Marigold is seventy if she's a day, flour to the elbows, a paper lantern half-folded in her hands and a Choir notice nailed to her door behind her like a death-warrant. She does not look at the notice. She looks at you, and her eyes are wet and absolutely undefeated.)* You'll be the Returned, then. *(she folds the lantern's last crease without looking down — forty years of hands.)* Good. Sit. Mind the dough. *(she sets the finished lantern on a shelf with a hundred others, every color.)* They've cancelled my feast. *(she nods, finally, at the notice.)* Forty years I've thrown the Lantern-Feast — one night, every harvest's-end, the whole Steelshanks ward in the square: fiddles, too much ale, the young ones courting under the lights, and at midnight we float the lanterns for whoever we lost that year. Marked and faithful, side by side, *dancing.* *(her jaw sets.)* And the Choir's served notice it's "frivolous in a time of holy sorrow." *(she laughs, short and hard.)* Holy sorrow. *(she meets your eyes.)* They don't care that it's *frivolous*, child. They care that it's *joyful.* A quarter full of the harvest-marked, *dancing*, *beloved*, *seen* — that's a quarter that's forgotten they're supposed to be *cargo.* *(she presses the half-folded lantern into your hands.)* So. The Choir says no feast. And I am seventy years old and out of forty years of patience. *Help* an old woman throw one more party they can't forgive.
  enter: SET sq.feast_thread_begun
  auto: 1
node: 1 | Dot Marigold
  *(She wipes her hands on her apron and lays it out plain, the way she'd lay out a recipe — because to Dot, this is one: equal parts defiance and joy, folded gently, never beaten.)* Here's the shape of it, and I'll not pretend it's safe. *(she counts on floury fingers.)* The Choir's notice means the Fist'll be watching the square. If we feast *open*, in defiance, on the night, in the *light* — that's a hundred witnesses to the harvest-marked being *people*, and it's a hundred necks under the Fist's eye. *(she folds a finger down.)* If we feast *quiet* — moved indoors, the cellars, the lanterns shuttered — then it's *safe*, and it *happens*, and nobody hangs, but it's a feast that agrees it should be *hidden.* *(another finger.)* Or — *(her voice softens, and goes somewhere old)* — we make it what it always half was, and stop pretending the dancing and the mourning are two different nights: we *feast* for the living and *float* for the dead in the *same* hour, joy and grief in one square, so nobody has to choose which one the night is *for.* *(she looks at the shelf of lanterns.)* I'm an old woman, Returned. This is the *last* feast I've the legs to run. After me — *(she stops.)* Well. That's the *other* question, isn't it. Whether there *is* an after-me. *(she meets your eyes, fierce and bright.)* So tell me. How does an old baker throw a party the harvest can't forgive — and should it be *brave*, or *safe*, or *whole*, or built to *outlast* the both of us?
  * "Hold it open, in the light, in defiance — the night, the square, every lantern lit. Let the Fist watch a hundred of the harvest-marked dance beloved and unafraid. The Choir cancelled it because joy among the doomed is the one thing they can't allow; so the answer is more joy, louder, in the exact square they forbade. A feast they can't forgive is a feast that proves the marked were never cargo." -> defiance | fx SET sq.feast_in_defiance
  * "Move it to the cellars, shutter the lanterns, keep it quiet and keep them living. A feast that happens is worth more than a feast that's brave — nobody floats a lantern for you next year if you hang for this one's. Let the Choir think they won. The fiddles still play; the young ones still court; the marked still dance. Hidden joy is still joy, and a dancer who lives to dance again has beaten them twice." -> secret | fx SET sq.feast_in_secret
  * "Make it whole — feast for the living and float for the dead in the same hour, in the same square. Stop letting them split the night into 'frivolous joy' and 'holy sorrow' as if a quarter can't do both. Dance AND grieve, courting under the same lights you launch the lanterns from. A feast that holds the loss and the joy together is one the Choir can't call frivolous OR forbid — because it's just a people being a people, whole." -> whole
  * "Whatever shape it takes, build it to outlast you. You said it yourself — this is the last feast you've the legs for. So teach it: the lantern-folds, the recipes, the midnight float, to hands young enough to run it for forty more years. The Choir can cancel a feast. They can't cancel a *tradition* that's already taught itself to a hundred children. Make the Lantern-Feast a thing the ward keeps, not a thing Dot does." -> endures | if sq.steelshanks_youth
  * "I can't take this on, Dot. The Choir's notice means the Fist, and I won't light a fuse in your square and walk off down my road while your ward pays for the spark. Throw a smaller fire than the one I'd leave you holding." -> defend
node: defiance | Dot Marigold
  *(She straightens to every inch of her seventy years, and the flour on her cheek catches the light like war-paint.)* Open. *(quietly, then not quietly.)* In the *light.* *Yes.* *(she takes the notice off her own door, slow, and folds it — into a lantern, creasing the Choir's seal into the paper's belly where the candle will sit.)* You know what they got *wrong*, child? *(she works the folds.)* They think a feast is *frivolous.* They think when they cancel the *dancing* they've cancelled something *small.* *(her hands move, sure.)* But the dancing was *never* small. The dancing is a hundred of the harvest-marked standing in a lit square in front of the *whole* *city* and *being* *beloved* — being *courted*, being *fed*, being *cheered* when they reel the figure right — being, for *one* *night*, *exactly* what the Wall says they *aren't*: *people*, *wanted*, *here.* *(she sets the Choir's notice, now a lantern, on a pole.)* The harvest *runs* on the marked being *invisible* — cargo, a number, a thing the comfortable can let happen because they never *see* it dance. *(fierce.)* So we will be *seen.* The *loudest*, *brightest*, most *unforgivably* *joyful* night Steelshanks ever threw, in the *exact* square they forbade, with the Choir's own notice *burning* at the top of the *first* *pole.* *(she meets your eyes, blazing.)* Let the Fist watch. Let them *count* us. A hundred names dancing is a hundred names the city *can't* *unsee* — and you can't *harvest* what the whole quarter's been *seen* to *love.* *(she presses the notice-lantern into your hands.)* *Light* it. *First* one up. Let them forgive *that.*
  enter: SET sq.feast_held_open, SET act1.mercy_remembered, SET faction.choir +1, appr.varra +6
  auto: 2
node: secret | Dot Marigold
  *(She considers it without an ounce of shame, the way only the genuinely brave can choose caution.)* Quiet. *(she nods slowly.)* The cellars. *(she begins gathering lanterns off the shelf, into a basket, shutters and all.)* You think me a coward for it? *(she doesn't wait.)* I'm not. I've buried forty years of this ward, child, and I learned a thing the brave young ones haven't yet: a *dead* dancer floats no lanterns *next* year. *(she packs another.)* The Choir *wants* us open. *Wants* the square, the witnesses, the Fist with a *reason.* A defiant feast in the light is a *list* — a hundred marked necks, named, counted, *convenient.* *(she meets your eyes, and they're hard and warm at once.)* So we don't *give* them the list. We give them a quiet they think they *won* — and *under* it, in the cellars, with the lanterns *shuttered* so no candle shows at the grate, the *fiddles* *still* *play.* The young ones *still* *court.* The marked *still* *dance.* *(her voice drops, fierce.)* Joy they can't *see* is joy they can't *stop*, and a feast that *survives* is a feast that happens *again*, and *again*, every harvest's-end, every year I've got and every year after — because nobody *hanged* for it. *(she ties the basket.)* Let the Choir take its little victory home. *(quietly, with a smile that has outlived governments.)* We'll be in the cellar, dancing, alive, ready to do it *all* again next year. *That's* how you beat a thing that's *betting* you'll be *brave* and *gone.* You be *joyful* and *here.*
  enter: SET sq.feast_held_secret, SET act5.unbroken_line, appr.roen +6
  auto: 2
node: whole | Dot Marigold
  *(Something in her face eases — the relief of an old woman hearing someone finally say the thing she's known for forty years and never had the words for.)* Whole. *(she breathes it.)* *Both* in the one hour. *(she sits, slow, and draws two lanterns to her — one bright-painted, one plain white.)* Forty years, child, I've watched them try to *split* it. The Choir says *dance* is frivolous and *grief* is holy, as though a body's only allowed *one* at a time, as though my ward must choose to be a *party* or a *funeral.* *(she sets the two lanterns side by side.)* But we were *never* either. *(her thumb moves between them.)* The same square where the girls court under the lights is the square where, at midnight, we float a lantern for the boy who *isn't* courting this year because the harvest took him. The *same* night. The *same* people. *Laughing* and *grieving* in the *same* *breath*, because that's — *(her voice catches)* — that's what a *people* *is.* Not a party. Not a funeral. A *whole* thing that *holds* its *joy* and its *loss* at *once* and refuses to be told it can only have *one.* *(she presses both lanterns into your hands — the bright and the white.)* So. We feast for the *living* AND float for the *dead*, same hour, same square, and we *dare* the Choir to call it frivolous *or* forbid it — because it's not a *celebration* and it's not a *mourning*, it's a *ward* being *human* out loud, and *that* they have *no* *doctrine* against. *(fierce, wet, smiling.)* Let them try to write the order that bans a people from *feeling* *everything* *at* *once.* *Light* them *both*, child. The bright one for the ones still here to dance. The white one for the ones we dance *for.*
  enter: SET sq.feast_whole, SET act1.mercy_remembered, SET act2.cataloguing_defeats_the_wall, appr.naeve +6
  auto: 2
node: endures | Dot Marigold
  *(She goes very still, and then her eyes fill — not with grief, but with the particular terror of an old maker who's afraid the thing she made will die with her.)* Outlast me. *(barely a whisper.)* ...You've named the thing I lie awake on, child. *(she looks at the shelf of a hundred lanterns, forty years of hands.)* It's not the Choir I'm afraid of. I've out-stubborned the Choir since before their high men were *born.* *(her voice tightens.)* It's *after.* I'm *seventy.* This is the *last* feast I've the *legs* to run — and I've been throwing it *alone*, the folds and the recipes and the order of the midnight float all in *my* old head, and when I *go* — *(she stops.)* When I go, the Choir doesn't *have* to cancel it. It just... *stops.* Because nobody *else* knows how. *(she meets your eyes, fierce through the wet.)* And a feast that dies with its baker is a feast the harvest *wins* by *waiting.* *(she stands, resolve hardening.)* So. *No.* Not this year. This year I *teach* it. The lantern-folds to the ward's children — every color, every crease. The recipes to the young bakers. The order of the float to whoever's got the voice for it. *(her hands move, already planning.)* I make the Lantern-Feast a thing the *ward* *keeps*, not a thing *Dot* *does* — taught to a hundred small hands young enough to run it for *forty* *more* *years*, and teach it to a hundred *more* after *them.* *(she meets your eyes, blazing.)* Let the Choir cancel a *feast.* I *dare* them to cancel a *tradition* that's already in the hands of every child in Steelshanks. You can hang a baker, child. *(fierce, triumphant.)* You can't hang a *recipe.* *Help* me *teach* it — so the lanterns go up *every* harvest's-end *long* after the old woman who folded the first one is *ash* on the *wind* with all the rest she ever loved.
  enter: SET sq.feast_endures, SET act5.unbroken_line, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.ilfaeril +6
  auto: 2
node: 2 | Dot Marigold
  *(Dot Marigold stands among forty years of paper lanterns — every color of a ward that refused to be only sorrowful — the Choir's notice already folded into a candle-holder, and looks at you with the particular joy of an old woman who has just been given permission to do the thing she was always going to do anyway.)*
  * "There's one more place a lantern should go this year — the Court at the end of the world, where the powers file the marked as 'nothing.' Carry one of Dot's lanterns there. Let them face the proof their doctrine can't survive: that the people they call cargo were *danced* with, *courted*, *cheered*, *beloved* — a whole quarter's joy, folded into paper, set burning in the room that says they were owed none." -> to_court | fx SET sq.feast_to_the_court, SET act5.the_great_objection
  * "Tell me the truth, Dot — forty years is a long time to throw the same party. Whose feast was the first one *for*? You don't fold a hundred lanterns a year for a *ward*. You started this for *someone.* Who?" -> whose_feast | fx appr.varra +3
  * "Whatever you do, don't throw it alone this year. You've carried this ward's joy on your own back for forty harvests — let the ward carry *you* for once. Bring in the others: the fiddler, the young bakers, the courting kids who think it's *their* feast now. Joy shared out is joy that can't be cancelled by arresting one old woman." -> not_alone | fx SET sq.feast_shared, SET act5.unbroken_line
node: to_court | Dot Marigold
  *(She chooses a lantern off the shelf — not the brightest, but a particular one, soft-gold, a little weathered — and holds it a moment before she gives it over.)* To the *Court.* *(slowly, then with rising fire.)* To the *powers* who *file* my dancers as *"nothing."* *(she presses the gold lantern into your hands.)* *Yes.* Take *this* one. *(she folds your fingers around it.)* You want to know what they can't *answer*, child — the powers, the Choir, the whole machine that says the marked are *owed* no *grief*, no *roof*, no *count*? *(fierce.)* It's not your arguments. It's not even your *dead.* It's the *joy.* *(she taps the lantern.)* They have a doctrine for *suffering* — the Faithless *earned* it, the Wall is *just*, every grief is *deserved.* But they have *no* *doctrine* for a quarter of the harvest-marked *dancing.* For a doomed girl being *courted* under the lights. For a marked man *cheered* when he reels the figure right. For an old baker folding a *hundred* *lanterns* a year because her ward, which the Wall says is *cargo*, is so *full* of *love* it *overflows* into *paper* and *fire.* *(she meets your eyes, blazing.)* You can call a *grief* deserved. You *cannot* look at *joy* — real, fierce, unbought joy among the doomed — and call *that* *nothing.* *(quietly, fiercely.)* So carry my lantern to the end of the world, and *light* it in the room that files my dancers to *zero*, and let the powers try to explain to a *burning* *paper* *full* of a *quarter's* *love* why the people who *made* it were *owed* *no* *grief.* *(she steps back.)* They built their machine against our *sorrow*, child. *(she smiles, terrible and bright.)* They never armored it against our *joy.* Go. *Burn* it where it'll *blind* them.
  enter: SET sq.feast_to_the_court, SET act5.the_great_objection, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.ilfaeril +5
  auto: close
node: whose_feast | Dot Marigold
  *(The fire goes out of her, gently, and she picks up the half-folded lantern again — not to work it, just to hold it, the way you hold a hand.)* Whose. *(softly.)* ...You don't miss much, do you. *(she creases the fold, slow.)* Tomas. My husband. *(she says it the way you say a name you've worn smooth.)* Forty-one years ago — first harvest after we wed — the marking came for the man two doors down, a fiddler, godless and *kind*, and the ward just... *closed* its shutters. Pretended it wasn't happening. Let him be taken in a *silence* so *thick* you could've *cut* it for *bread.* *(her jaw works.)* And Tomas — my Tomas, who couldn't carry a tune in a *bucket* — Tomas said, *"That's not how we send a man off. Not in silence. Not pretending."* *(her eyes fill.)* So he dragged every fiddle in Steelshanks into the square that night and made us *play.* For the taken man. *Loud.* Made us *dance*, so the last thing the poor godless fiddler heard from his ward wasn't *shutters* — it was his *neighbors*, *refusing* to pretend he was *nothing*, *seeing* him *off* with *joy.* *(she meets your eyes.)* That was the first Lantern-Feast. Tomas's idea. *(quietly.)* The harvest took Tomas himself, nine years on. And I have folded a hundred lanterns a year, every year since, because my husband taught me the one thing the whole machine can't *stand*: that you *see* *people* *off* with *music*, not *silence* — that *joy*, *out* *loud*, in the *teeth* of the *harvest*, is how a ward says *"we will not pretend you were nothing."* *(she sets the lantern down.)* Forty years, child. Every one of them is Tomas, refusing to let a single soul in this ward be *taken* in *silence.* *Help* me throw *one* *more.* For all of them. For *him.*
  enter: SET sq.feast_for_tomas, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.varra +5
  auto: close
node: not_alone | Dot Marigold
  *(She laughs — a real one, surprised out of her — and sets down the lantern.)* Don't throw it *alone.* *(she shakes her head, rueful.)* Forty years and it never *once* occurred to me. *(she looks at her own flour-caked hands.)* I've carried this ward's joy on my *own* back so long I forgot it was ever meant to be *shared* out — that a feast *thrown* by one old woman is a feast that can be *cancelled* by *arresting* one old woman. *(her eyes sharpen.)* But you're right, and it's *better* than right — it's *safer* AND it's *truer.* *(she starts counting on her fingers, delighted.)* Old Fenn and his fiddle. The Aldermarket girls who think the courting-dances are *theirs* now — let them. The young bakers who've been *sneaking* my lantern-recipe for *years*, badly. The *children*, gods, the children who fold the paper better than I do already. *(she meets your eyes, blazing.)* If the feast belongs to *all* of them — if a *hundred* hands light it, fold it, *run* it — then the Choir can't *end* it by ending *me.* You can arrest a *baker*, child. *(fierce, joyful.)* You can't arrest a *whole* *ward* that's decided, *together*, to be *joyful* *out* *loud.* *(she claps the flour off her hands, ready.)* So *that's* what we do. Not *Dot's* feast. *Steelshanks'* feast — every hand in it, so *no* *one* *hand's* *loss* can *stop* it. *(she grins, seventy years and undefeated.)* I've been the lonely old woman who *throws* the party. Time I was just *one* *more* *dancer* *in* *it.* *Help* me give it *away* — to *everyone* — so it *outlives* us *all.*
  enter: SET sq.feast_shared, SET act5.unbroken_line, SET act1.mercy_remembered, appr.roen +5
  auto: close
node: defend | Dot Marigold
  *(She sighs, and the fire banks — not out, just covered, the way an old baker covers coals to keep them through a cold night.)* No stomach for it. *(she nods, without judgment.)* That's honest, at least. *(she sets the half-folded lantern back on the shelf, unfinished.)* It's a dangerous thing I'm asking, and you've a longer road than my one square. *(she meets your eyes, and there's no anger in it, only an old woman's patience.)* But think on it, on that road of yours. *(quietly.)* They didn't cancel my feast because it was *frivolous*, child. They cancelled it because they're *afraid* of it — afraid of a quarter of the doomed *dancing*, *beloved*, *seen.* *(she folds her hands.)* A thing the powers are *afraid* of is a thing worth *throwing*, however *small* it looks. *(she turns back to her lanterns.)* The square's there if you change your mind. So am I — for a while yet. *(softly, to the lanterns more than to you.)* Forty years. I'll not stop now for *want* of *help.* I'll just fold a little *slower.* *(and she takes up the unfinished lantern again, creasing it gently, an old woman who will throw her party with or without you, because joy in the teeth of the harvest was never a thing she did for *thanks*.)*
  auto: close
node: close | Dot Marigold
  *(Dot Marigold stands among forty years of paper lanterns — folded by hands that buried a husband and half a ward and never once let a soul be taken in silence — and whether you lit the Choir's own notice at the top of the first pole, hid the dancing safe in the cellars, wove the joy and the grief into one whole human night, taught the feast to a hundred small hands so it outlives her, carried a soft-gold lantern to the Court to blind the powers with a quarter's overflowing love, drew out the name of the tuneless husband who started it all, or gave the feast away to the whole ward so no single arrest could end it, you carry away the one weapon the entire long road of the dead never handed you: not grief, not testimony, not rescue, but *joy* — fierce, unbought, out loud, among the doomed — the single thing the harvest-machine was never built to answer, because you can call a sorrow deserved, but no doctrine in any heaven can look at a marked girl being courted under the lights and call *that* *nothing*.)*
